{{pp-semi|small=yes}} {{Use Indian English|date=June 2015}} {{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}} {{Infobox militant organization |name = Banga Sena |logo = |caption = |dates = |leader = Kalidas Baidya |motives = The creation of a separate [[Hinduism|Hindu]] [[Bangabhumi|state]] comprising [[Bangladesh]], [[West Bengal]], [[Assam]], and other parts of [[Northeast India]] |area = [[Bangladesh]] |ideology = [[Hindu Nationalism]], [[Separatism]], [[Communalism]] |crimes = According to Bangladeshi sources, the Banga Sena is involved in insurgency activities against Bangladesh. |attacks = |status = }}
The '''Banga Sena''' ({{lang-en|'''Bengal Army'''}}) is a [[Separatism|separatist]]<ref name=TELEGRAPH>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1040107/asp/nation/story_2760337.asp|title=Dhaka seeks proof, Delhi readies maps|author=Seema Guha|date=2004-01-07|accessdate=2008-06-30|publisher=''[[The Telegraph (Kolkata)|The Telegraph]]''}}</ref> [[Hinduism|Hindu]] organization which advocates formation of a [[Bangabhumi|separate homeland]] for [[Hinduism in Bangladesh|Bengali Hindus]] in [[Bangladesh]].<ref name=INDIAINFO>{{cite web|url=http://news.indiainfo.com/2003/02/18/18held.html |title=400 Banga Sena activists held at Bangla border |date=2003-02-18 |accessdate=2008-06-30 |publisher=''Indiainfo.com'' |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080904233910/http://news.indiainfo.com/2003/02/18/18held.html |archivedate=4 September 2008 }}</ref> The group is led by Kalidas Baidya.<ref name=TELEGRAPH/> {{Persecution of Bengali Hindus}}
[[Major General]] Jahangir Alam Chowdhury, the Director General of the [[Bangladesh Rifles]] (BDR), in a talk with the Director General of the [[Border Security Force]] (BSF) Ajay Raj Sharma in 2004 said that the extremist group Banga Sena was carrying out [[Terrorism|terrorist]] and [[secession]]ist activities against Bangladesh from its bases in the Indian state of [[West Bengal]].<ref name=DAILYSTARBDRBSFABC>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/2004/01/11/d40111011212.htm|title=BDR, BSF agree to bust camps|author=Pallab Bhattacharya|date=2004-01-11|accessdate=2008-06-30|publisher=''[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]''}}</ref> Khodeza Begum in an article in the ''[[Global Politician]]'' accused [[India]] of helping to organize the Banga Sena.<ref name=GLOBALPOLITICIAN>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalpolitician.com/21944-india|title=Indian move to establish United India through United Bengal|date=2006-07-14|author=Khodeza Begum|accessdate=2008-06-30|publisher=''[[Global Politician]]''|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080530171251/http://globalpolitician.com/21944-india|archivedate=30 May 2008|deadurl=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In March 2006, a senior official of the home ministry of Bangladesh expressed concern over the anti-Bangladesh activities by the Banga Sena. Regarding this he added that Bangladesh wants a peaceful border with neighboring India and the situation has vastly improved following coordinated border patrolling by the both countries.<ref name=DAILYSTARKMMINE>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/2006/03/15/d60315060170.htm|title=Khaleda-Manmohan meet on March 21 to initiate new era|date=2006-03-15|accessdate=2008-06-30|publisher=''[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]''}}</ref> A Bangladeshi official stated that the organization is a "threat to the sovereignty of Bangladesh".<ref name=KIVBBL>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsnetwork-bd.com/UI/Public/NewsDetail.php?LogID=11409 |title=Khaleda’s India visit to boost bilateral ties |date=2006-03-15 |accessdate=2008-06-30}}{{dead link|date=May 2016}}{{cbignore}}</ref>
More than 400 members of the Banga Sena were arrested in India on February 18, 2003 for trying to cross over into Bangladesh from the district of [[North 24 Parganas district|North 24 Parganas]] in southern West Bengal. According to police sources, activists belonging to the organization began gathering at the Indo-Bangladesh border at Halencha, North 24 Parganas in the jurisdiction of the Bagda police station since morning that day.<ref name=INDIAINFO/>
In January 2004, the director general of the Bangladesh Rifles gave a list of the camps of the remaining Shanti Bahni elements in the [[North-East India]]n states of [[Tripura]] and [[Assam]] and in adjoining Indian provinces to the director general of the Border Security Force. The list documented that the Banga Sena, along with several other groups, carried out communal tension and separatist activities against Bangladesh from West Bengal. Indian Foreign Secretary said that India will cooperate in tackling the Banga Sena and other [[Insurgency|insurgent]] groups.<ref name=IHTABI>{{cite web|url=http://www.bangladesh-web.com/view.php?hidType=NAT&hidRecord=0000000000000000003363|title=India to help tackle anti-Bangladesh insurgents|date=2004-03-12|accessdate=2008-06-30}}</ref> On September 2007, the representatives of two [[Non-governmental organization|NGOs]], Diphu Citizen Peace Forum and Karbi Human Rights Watch, in the [[Karbi Anglong District]] of Assam said that the Banga Sena was involved in [[extortion]] and it could pose a threat to the peace in the region.<ref name=ONEINDIAMOBILE>{{cite web|url=http://news.oneindia.mobi/2007/09/03/429222.html|title=Organisations appeal for public support for peace in Karbi Anglong|date=2007-09-03|accessdate=2008-06-30|publisher=''[[Oneindia Mobile]]''}}{{dead link|date=May 2016}}</ref> Regarding the activities of the Banga Sena, the Foreign Secretary of Bangladesh Shamsher Mobin Chowdhury made it clear that his country will not tolerate any statement or move against its territory or sovereignty.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ashraf |first=Nazmul |date=2003-02-21 |title=Bangladesh ready to evacuate citizens from Middle East |url=http://gulfnews.com/news/uae/general/bangladesh-ready-to-evacuate-citizens-from-middle-east-1.347945 |newspaper=Gulf News |accessdate=2008-06-30}}</ref> The All India Minority Forum, an organization for religious minorities in India, also expressed concern over this organization.<ref>{{cite news |title=Minority forum flays PM's remarks on Ayodhya |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/38298464.cms |date=2003-02-22 |newspaper=[[The Times of India]] |accessdate=2008-06-30}}</ref>
