In United States [[agriculture|agricultural]] policy, the '''make allowance''' (or '''milk manufacturing marketing adjustment''') is the [[Margin (economics)|margin]] between the government [[support price]] for [[milk]] and the [[Commodity Credit Corporation]] (CCC) purchase price for butter, nonfat [[dry milk]], and cheese. This margin is administratively set to cover the costs of “making” milk into butter, nonfat dry milk, or cheese to reach the desired level of prices for milk in [[manufacturing]] uses.

