'''Sisyphism''' is a term used by French [[classical liberalism|classical liberal]] theorist, [[political economy|political economist]], and member of the French assembly, [[Frédéric Bastiat]] to ridicule those that think that greater [[productivity]] causes [[poverty]] by increasing [[unemployment]]. The term derives form [[Sisyphus]], the [[Greek mythology|mythological]] king of [[Cichyrus|Ephyra]], punished for chronic deceitfulness by being compelled to roll an immense boulder up a hill, only to watch it roll back down, and to repeat this action forever.<ref>[[Frédéric Bastiat|Bastiat, Frédéric]]; Walter, Emile (transl.). ''What Is Free Trade?''. Chapter&nbsp;III. p.&nbsp;10. Available at [http://www.gutenberg.org/catalog/world/readfile?fk_files=187068&pageno=10 Project Gutenberg]</ref>
