{{distinguish|South African Indian Congress}}
The '''South African Indian Council''' was a body created by the [[South Africa under Apartheid|apartheid-era]] South African government in 1968 to make recommendations to the government about matters affecting [[Indian South Africans|Indians]].  It was the first time that Indians were granted any sort of representation at the national level.  Nonetheless, it was widely rejected by South African Indians (in the 1981 election for example, only 6% of them voted). 

In 1974, it was reconstituted as a body where 50% of the members were elected by Indians. 

[[Amichand Rajbansi]]'s [[National People's Party (South Africa, 1981)|National People's Party]] dominated the council, as it did the later [[House of Delegates of South Africa|House of Delegates]] in the [[Tricameral Parliament]], although neither body enjoyed the support of the majority of Indians. [http://www.nelsonmandela.org/omalley/index.php/site/q/03lv03445/04lv03446/05lv03503.htm]

